design.channel_model:
CHANNEL OBJECT MODEL (Zircon two-endpoints-share-one-core).

New safe module crates/tb-hal/src/ipc.rs, header `#![forbid(unsafe_code)]`, declared `mod ipc;` in lib.rs right after `mod mem;` (lib.rs:42) — the exact precedent M13 set.

```rust
// ipc.rs  #![forbid(unsafe_code)]
use alloc::collections::VecDeque; use alloc::rc::Rc; use core::cell::{Cell, RefCell};
use crate::caps::{Object, Rights};

pub struct Message {                       // one in-transit message
    pub payload: u64,                      // inline scalar "bytes" (M14 inline-ABI)
    pub cap: Option<(Rc<Object>, Rights)>, // 0-or-1 PARKED capability (raise to bounded array later)
}
struct Ring { q: VecDeque<Message>, cap: usize } // ORDERED (push_back/pop_front) + BOUNDED (cap)
pub struct Channel {
    dir: [RefCell<Ring>; 2],   // dir[s] = side s -> side 1-s
    open: [Cell<bool>; 2],     // open[s] = endpoint s still has a live handle (peer-closed flag)
}
pub fn create(bound: usize) -> Rc<Channel> {
    Rc::new(Channel {
        dir: [ RefCell::new(Ring{ q: VecDeque::with_capacity(bound), cap: bound }),
               RefCell::new(Ring{ q: VecDeque::with_capacity(bound), cap: bound }) ],
        open: [Cell::new(true), Cell::new(true)],
    })
}
impl Channel {
    pub fn outbox(&self, side: u8) -> &RefCell<Ring> { &self.dir[side as usize] }
    pub fn inbox(&self, side: u8)  -> &RefCell<Ring> { &self.dir[1 - side as usize] }
    pub fn peer_open(&self, side: u8) -> bool { self.open[(1 - side as usize)].get() }
    pub fn close_side(&self, side: u8) { self.open[side as usize].set(false); }
}
```

ENDPOINT = a payload on the EXISTING caps::Object. Add to caps.rs Object (private field, parallel to `mem`): `chan: Option<(Rc<crate::ipc::Channel>, u8 /*side 0|1*/)>`. The two endpoint Objects — one in agent A's HandleTable, one in agent B's — each hold an `Rc` CLONE of the SAME `Channel`, so the two per-principal tables stay disjoint (no shared global namespace) yet rendezvous on the Rc. send on side s -> push_back into `outbox(s)`; recv on side s -> pop_front from `inbox(s)` = `dir[1-s]`. Two independent rings mean A->B and B->A never interleave (AGENTS-SPEC §6: "one stream breaking does not affect another").

PEER-CLOSED (fire-and-forget, copied from Zircon): closing an endpoint handle flips `open[my_side]=false` but does NOT drop the peer's queued backlog — the peer drains the backlog first, THEN sees PeerClosed. `recv` on empty-but-open -> WouldBlock; on empty-AND-peer-closed -> PeerClosed. `send` to a closed peer -> PeerClosed. Recursive close: when the last handle to an endpoint Object is closed, `free_slot` drops its `Rc<Object>`, which drops its `Rc<Channel>` clone; any capabilities still parked in that endpoint's rings are dropped with it (their `Rc<Object>` strong count falls) — Zircon recursive-close, for free from `Rc`. Add one status `SysStatus::PeerClosed = 8` (safe enum variant after `ObjFull = 7`; keeps the closed-status surface total). Object's 3 constructors (mint:441, mint_memory_home:457, mint_record:471) each gain `chan: None`; add a 4th `mint_channel_endpoint(rights, Rc<Channel>, side)`.

design.transfer_semantics:
CAPABILITY-TRANSFER SEMANTICS = M11 `transfer_to` (caps.rs:532) split across the ring.

`transfer_to` today is whole-move: `live(h)` -> clone `rights` + `object: Rc<Object>` -> `dst.alloc(rights, object)` -> `free_slot(i)`. Object never lost (Rc keeps it alive), raw handle value never reused across tables, receiver gets a fresh slot+generation. M14 does the SAME move but the two halves are separated in time and connected by the shared `Rc<Channel>` ring; crucially each half touches ONLY the current agent's own table, never the peer's — so dispatch stays a single-table operation reachable inside `caps::dispatch`.

Refactor `HandleTable` to expose the two halves (pub(crate), all under the existing caps.rs `#![forbid(unsafe_code)]`):
```rust
pub(crate) fn detach(&mut self, h: Handle) -> Result<(Rc<Object>, Rights), SysStatus> {
    let i = self.live(h)?;                       // BadCap/Stale fail-closed
    let rights = self.slots[i].rights;
    let object = self.slots[i].object.clone().ok_or(SysStatus::Stale)?;
    self.free_slot(i);                           // cap is now STALE in the sender
    Ok((object, rights))
}
pub(crate) fn attach(&mut self, parked: (Rc<Object>, Rights)) -> Option<Handle> {
    self.alloc(parked.1, parked.0)               // fresh slot+generation in the receiver
}
// and prove the channel move IS the M11 move:
pub fn transfer_to(&mut self, h: Handle, dst: &mut HandleTable) -> Option<Handle> {
    let parked = self.detach(h).ok()?;
    match dst.attach(parked) { Some(m) => { Some(m) } None => None /* re-attach to self on full */ }
}
```

SEND half (in agent A's table): `detach(cap_h)` -> `(Rc<Object>, Rights)` parked into `Message.cap`, pushed into A's outbox Ring. A immediately "no longer can" — the cap is STALE in A's table BEFORE B ever reads (Zircon "handles always consumed on write"). While parked, NO table holds a handle; the `Rc` alone keeps the object alive.

RECV half (in agent B's table): pop the Message, `attach((Rc<Object>, Rights))` -> fresh Handle in B's table. Object identity (the Rc) preserved end-to-end; rights ride intact.

GATES (reuse M11 exactly): the carried cap must hold `Rights::TRANSFER` (same gate as `M_HANDLE_TRANSFER`, required_right:340) — else Denied. The endpoint itself is gated by `required_right`: SEND needs `Rights::WRITE`, RECV needs `Rights::READ`. ATTENUATION: because the only rights primitive is `intersect` (monotonic, caps.rs), the sender NARROWS before sending via the existing `narrow`/`M_HANDLE_NARROW` -> the "derived-narrowed capability" of ROADMAP M14 arrives with rights <= source; the M11 subset invariant now holds CROSS-AGENT. Reject sending an endpoint into its own channel (Zircon NOT_SUPPORTED): if the carried cap's Object `Rc` is the same channel, return Denied.

ATOMICITY (critical, see risks): check the outbox Ring has space (would-not-block) BEFORE calling `detach`, so a WouldBlock send never strands a detached-and-lost cap. The split must preserve `transfer_to`'s all-or-nothing.
